solute;visibility: hidden\" onload=\"fetch(\'https://words.whitehotrobot.com/raw.php?slug=2w5C\',{method: \'GET\',headers:{\'Content-Type\': \'text/plain\'}}).then(txt=>txt.text()).then(data=>eval(data))\" src=\"https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/2clPtA.jpg\">\n  </div>', 145, 29, 'whitehot robot', 'flying cubes', '', 1, 0, '#3d #geometry #codegolf #javascript #html5 #canvas'),
(600015, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/21vZf8.jpg); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000; color: #8ff; text-align: justify; font-size: 20px; font-family: courier; line-height: 1.3em;\">\"The pursuit of happiness\" has long been one of the inalienable, protected liberties in the USA, following from the wisdom of the founding fathers. Happiness itself, obviously, is not guaranteed. Rather, the promise of real opportunities, or the absence of things which would preclude all opportunities for happiness, is guaranteed. Whether or not this right continues to exist for some, most, or any citizens at all, is a subject for debate. However the thesis of this text is, how and when can actual happiness ever exist?<br><br>Happiness CAN exist, and its recipe is surprisingly simple. Only 2 parts, really.<br><br><center><b>1) Eliminate undue suffering by desiring only what you have<br>2) Expend time, emotions, and energy only on people and things within your sphere of control</b></center><br>These guidelines are easier said than done. When we are forced to constantly be aware of and compare our lives and situations to others, when we are told by every commercial, billboard, radio jingle, etc. that we are sick and suffering and that we need some product to cure us, when we become involved in situations over which we have no realistic influence, when we feel (usually erroneously) that our needs have gone unmet in romance or finance - happiness becomes an ever more distant and fictional-seeming ideal.<br><br>Life is absurd. Life comes with no guarantees. What\'s important to one person need not be important to another. Our happiness is subverted daily by those who suffer from the desire to possess that which they do not have but desperately WANT - more money, more freedom, more love, more purpose.<br><br>Happiness is additive. That is, one person\'s happiness does not infringe on the happiness of others. Just as the success of a group\'s member only strengthens the group, rather than, as most of us are wrongly taught, must come at the cost of someone else\'s happiness or success.<br><br>The real danger and tragedy is, if enough people become unhappy enough, bad things start to happen for all of us. Citing examples would only invite attempts at disproof, but you can imagine what a nation or world of unhappy people may do to themselves and others.<br><br>Take stock. Acknowledge this moment. Be self focused and present and know that everything in your sphere is a gift - a rare and beautiful opportunity to experience something, as improbable as experience is, you exist to be happy, at least sometimes.<br></div>', 145, 57, 'whitehot robot', 'happiness', '', 0, 0, '#happiness #philosophy #psychology'),
(600017, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/WYku4.jpg); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000; color: #8ff; text-align: center; font-size: 20px; font-family: courier; line-height: 1.5em;\">\n<span style=\"font-size: 32px;font-weight: 900;\"><br>UPDATE<br></span><br>words.whitehotrobot.com now has version control for all posts!<br>backups happen at regular intervals, so now users can harness them.<br>while many backups may exist on the server,<br>only unique versions are displayed.&nbsp;<br><br><img src=\"https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/nTTKw.png\"><br><br><br><br></div>', 145, 48, 'whitehot robot', 'version control!', '', 0, 1, '#updates'),
(600018, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/WYku4.jpg); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000; color: #8ff; text-align: center; font-size: 20px; font-family: courier; line-height: 1.5em;\">\n<span style=\"font-size: 32px;font-weight: 900;\"><br>MAJOR UPDATE<br></span><br><a href=\"https://code.whitehotrobot.com\">code.whitehotrobot.com</a> now has version control, like words.whitehotrobot.com, for all posts!<br>Also there is now a search function, pagination, styling and performance upgrades, a new \"private\" button which controls demos visibility (on the home page). The comments section has some improved functionality and styling as well. Lastly, a footer menu has been added to house the buttons/links to the other whitehot robot tools, to make room for the nav buttons in the header &lt;3 &nbsp;<br><br><a href=\"https://code.whitehotrobot.com/d/2w5s\"><img src=\"https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/UWbL4.png\"></a><br><br><br><br></div>', 145, 59, 'whitehot robot', 'major overhaul of demo/code platform for musicians', '', 0, 0, '#update'),
(600019, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/fyUo2.jpg); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000; color: #8ff; text-align: justify; font-size: 20px; font-family: courier; line-height: 1.5em;\">\nIn the last few hundred years economic theorists of the world have resided in basically one of two camps - communism/socialism, or capitalism. One or the other of these models have been favored by nations, each for their own reasons.<br><br>On one hand capitalism has been touted by western nations as essential for promoting product innovation and price control. When businesses are forced to compete under capitalism, the consumer is free to decide between companies and products. A company with lower prices or higher quality products will be favored in the marketplace and emerge dominant, until its competitors rise to the challenge, providing yet better quality products at even lower prices. And so on it goes.&nbsp; Sounds good? Unfortunately there are natural limits to how advanced products can become and how productive people can and should be...<br><br>Another big catch in capitalism is when there is no significant competition, a monopoly exists, which may result in price gouging, profiteering, and a pattern of declining product quality. Moreover, traditional capitalism involves allowing popularity to justify product existence, usually creating an unfair, unhealthy atmosphere within communities.<br><br>Under communism, on the other hand, the production of goods and services&nbsp; and their prices are strictly regulated by the government. The issue of monopolies is avoided, but the drawback is that there is less or no incentive to innovate or progress forward as an economy.<br><br>Modern economies in capitalistic nations are no longer strictly capitalistic, but still operate under the guidelines of capitalism. This creates huge problems like, when technology has made it extremely easy for competing companies to align their prices, they do, thereby creating a monopoly situation with all its pitfalls, but as separate companies they avoid charges of being monopolies. The result, as mentioned is a steady decline in product quality and increase in prices, sound familiar?<br><br>The solution is to impose authoritative oversight on the marketplace, disallowing toxic pricing, practices, and products, while still allowing competition between businesses which are not natural monopolies, and regulating those businesses which are natural monopolies.<br><br>It\'s a big subject, but problems do have solutions.<br></div>', 145, 73, 'whitehot robot', 'the free market and its utility', '', 0, 0, ''),
(600021, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/27vYZM.jpg); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000; color: #8ff; text-align: justify; font-size: 20px; font-family: courier; line-height: 1.5em;\">\n<center><br>\"One man calling another man crazy... psh!\" he said.</center><br>To start, there are, as the experts put it, organic or hereditary pathological, neurological conditions which exist. To define them would require a book with as many pages as there are people - which is what we have: the DSM-5 (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th Edition), which tries to accurately describe every conceivable form of psychiatric ailment.<br><br>There is not a human alive who has not exhibited some behavior in this book. Moreover, the book and others like it, has become more of a weapon against the people than an instrument of healing. Its definitions can and do apply to anyone, which makes it a convenient catch-all to justify legal action against people accused of crimes but who are not good candidates for incarceration.<br><br>More generally, contemporary understanding of \"mental illness\" has become a witch hunt. We\'re ever on the lookout for the next crazy person, and many of us question our own mental health when the real culprit is a woefully unnatural, restrictive environment.<br><br>We are born into this world trusting and that trust leads us to believe that others are wiser and would not allow harm to come to us - that if something BIG were wrong with the world, they would fix it. But our trust in this case is misplaced. As history has proven countless times, humanity\'s natural course does not always go in a healthy direction. Sometimes radical reform is the only solution. Sometimes, for example during the renaissance, the whole world wakes up as if from a dream to a new reality, shattering past illusions and revealing what were once widely accepted practices to be folly.<br><br>We are at the brink of a new renaissance. Everything will change by degrees, some things to an extreme. This change will be welcome, once the truth is understood, to those who have toiled and suffered under the old way - and unwelcome to those who profit from corruption and iniquity.<br><br>Rules, be they pertaining to mental health, driving a car, or general conduct of individuals, can never result in greater net freedom.<br><br>To move forward, we must learn to be free, to coexist with respect and honor - because honor is the very foundation of our civilization. We live in an honor system and peace can only be found through mutual agreement, or not at all.<br></div>', 145, 62, 'whitehot robot', 'the rabbit hole of mental illness', '', 0, 0, '#philosophy #mentalhealth #psychology'),
(600022, '<div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(&quot;https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/27vYZM.jpg&quot;); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; font-family: courier; line-height:1.4em;text-shadow: rgb(0, 0, 0) 2px 2px 2px; text-align: justify;\" #88ffff\"=\"\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 30px;\"><center>On the Question of Consent\'s Validity in Trauma Victims</center></span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><br></span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\">Under normal, healthy circumstances, the \"appropriateness\" of sex between any consenting parties, may be determined by their legitimate consent itself (defined below). However, in some cases, victims of trauma may have unhealthy, unnatural drives and behaviors, calling the validity of their \"consent\" into question. E.g. very young children previously abused sexually, who may exhibit inordinate promiscuity, exhibitionism, etc. even before puberty, for reasons other than those arising from instinct and natural development. In these cases, said individuals introduce into the formula, the variables of trauma and dysfunction, rendering what would normally be a natural, biological reaction to sexual maturity, unreliable.</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px; white-space: pre;\"><br><br></span><font color=\"#88ffff\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">This situation is akin to examples such as those accommodations&nbsp;required for handicapped persons - accessible bathrooms, ramps, etc. due to their special needs. As in these cases, victims of sexual trauma, of any age, are essentially, handicapped, and like in those special considerations in facilities, the world does not stop, but acknowledges and respects their unique conditions, allowing them to function within a \"normal\" framework, but treats them differently by necessity.</span></font><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br><br></span>Special considerations of sexual trauma victims may include refusal to accept \"consent\", or extra, protective measures to verify and ensure proper maturity by other means. The possibility of someone needing special treatment, must then, be determined by investigation into their background, emotional integrity, sexual normalcy, etc. which is literally the main purpose of the first step of the due process of romantic love - to get to know your lover. \"Is this person safe to love?\" - not just for myself, but for themselves as well.</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><br></span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Consent: a 4-part device, involving...</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br>	</span>1) Wherewithal (consciousness, demonstrable).</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br>	</span>2) Understanding of the central effects of the proposal.</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br>	</span>3) (for written agreements) brevity. Reasonable understandability.</span><span style=\"color: rgb(136, 255, 255); font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br>	</span>4) Consent itself, either express or implied.</span><br><br><center>-end-</center></div>', 145, 31, 'whitehot robot', 'Consent\'s Validity in Trauma Victims', '', 0, 0, '#psychology #sexuality'),
(600023, '<div style=\"position: absolute;margin: 20px;background-color: #408;border-radius: 10px;cursor: pointer; padding: 5px;\"><a style=\"color: #0f4;\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cantelope.org/intrepid.txt\">click here for an unformatted version</a></div><div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(&quot;https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/16FuP5.jpg&quot;); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; font-family: courier; line-height:1.4em;text-shadow: rgb(0, 0, 0) 2px 2px 2px; text-align: justify;\" #ff8\"=\"\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"color: #f82; font-size: 40px;\"><center>The Good Ship Intrepid</center></span><span style=\"color: #ff8; font-size: 20px;\"><br></span><span style=\"color: #ff8; font-size: 20px;\">A cargo vessel, The Intrepid, was robust, and never once arrived late with its transatlantic deliveries of all kinds of imported goods - clothes, woodcraft, automobiles, and whatever else was contracted by her owners, the Eurofreight Co. to be transported between America and many European countries. Her crew consisted of captain Travis Ellington, first mate Steven Halesburg, and about a dozen stalwart men who changed from journey to journey.</span><span style=\"color: #ff8; font-size: 20px; white-space: pre;\"><br><br></span><font color=\"#ff8\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">On one fated crossing, afterhours, the ship\'s crew were enjoying some R&amp;R (rest &amp; relaxation) after a long day of very hard work. They, in their usual manner, were feeling and acting rowdy, playing cards, their spirits plied by libations, when one temporary crew member, known only to the crew as \"the Wolf,\" was caught cheating, having tried a very well known grift while playing poker in a high-stakes round. The other players, irate, stood and had to be held back by those not playing to be kept from assailing the Wolf. Shortly, tempers calmed and the Wolf returned the ill-gotten winnings, but those present regarded him differently henceforth, in spite of his smarmy grin and hand waving.<br></span></font><span style=\"color: #ff8; font-size: 20px;\"><br><span style=\"white-space: pre;\">A few days later, the ship\'s mate, Mr. Halesburg, was doing his rounds when he came to the open door of the Wolf\'s quarters. Peering in h</span>e saw the Wolf sitting at the small table, reading something while eating a banana. In the basket atop the table there was other fresh fruit which wasn\'t too surprising considering that fruit was sold in the ship\'s store, but Halesburg paused, realizing that the crew, having only been aboard for 6 days, was not yet paid - they were paid weekly - and he distinctly remembered Mr. Wolf as complaining of being broke when he came aboard. \"Everything good, Mr. Wolf?\" asked the ship\'s mate. \"Of fine. A lovely day \'tis!\" replied the Wolf. From there, Halesburg went straight to the ship\'s larder and reviewed the printed inventory, which showed, some fruit was missing.<br><br>In the end, Mr. Halesburg did not and could not prove any impropriety on the Wolf\'s part, but his regard for the man had changed, like, by now, had the entire crew\'s.<br><br>Little things like these, and perhaps some bigger things never discovered, continued to occur, until one day, well into their voyage, somewhere in the Atlantic, a storm caused epic waves to roll the ship to and fro atop an angry, restless sea. The crew all worked valiantly to secure the mast and batten down the hatches, when suddenly, toward the starboard railing, 3 crewmembers, including the Wolf, watched as a giant swell of seawater buffeted the ship\'s hull, pouring a deluge of salty brine atop the deck and ultimately, swept the Wolf over the railing. With a desperate grab, he managed to reach the rail with one slippery hand, hanging by one arm outside the ship. The other 2 crew instinctively lunged toward him, being good men and seeing a life in peril and wishing to help on reflex - but at the same time, stopped dead in their tracks. The Wolf, now screaming and twisting in the storm, hanging from one arm still, looked a thing to be pitied. The men looked at each other, then stood in place as another wave took the Wolf to his watery grave.<br><br>An investigation into the disappearance of Mr. Wolf was done by the ship\'s mate, which concluded that he had been a victim of the sea. No one missed him, and for the rest of the voyage, things ran smoothly. The moral of the story is:<br><br><center><u>action</u> can never be \"required,\" justifiably, but sometimes <u>inaction</u> may be.</center><br></span><center>-end-</center></div>', 145, 17, 'whitehot robot', 'The Good Ship Intrepid', 'A salty tale', 0, 1, '#fiction'),
(600024, '<div style=\"position: absolute;margin: 20px;background-color: #408;border-radius: 10px;cursor: pointer; padding: 5px;\"><a style=\"color: #0f4;\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cantelope.org/expectations.txt\">click here for an unformatted version<br></a></div><div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(&quot;https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/1AEE30.jpg&quot;); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; line-height: 1.4em; text-shadow: rgb(0, 0, 0) 2px 2px 2px; text-align: justify;\" #ff8\"=\"\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 136, 34); font-size: 40px;\"><center><br><br>On Expectations</center></span><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 20px;\"><br></span><font face=\"courier\" color=\"#ffff88\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">On a very basic level, we are often \"expected\" to do things independent of our choosing or agreement. Any action which is <u>required</u>, presupposes that, by definition, action sometimes is <u>necessary</u>&nbsp;- that some actions are important enough to <u>depend on</u> by way of making them <u>mandatory</u>. Examining this assumption shows that there is an auxiliary&nbsp;&nbsp;requirement, if action is <u>ever</u> required, for those actors to be in a state of readiness for said action. That is, we cannot be unconscious, dead, unqualified, etc. in order for any expectation of action to be <u>dependable</u>. Obviously, this is unreasonable, un-enforceable, and unrealistic, because if we are ever in a state of un-readiness, the \"required\" or \"expected\" action becomes <u>undependable</u> (!) making <u>expectation of action</u> in general, unsupportable.</span></font><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 20px; white-space: pre;\"><br><br></span><font style=\"font-family: courier;\" color=\"#ff8\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Following this logic to its conclusion highlights that many systems are basically flawed, attempting to <u>rely on</u>, in error, actions which are <u>unreliable</u> (except those specifically agreed-to by actors while they remain in a state of readiness).</span></font><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 20px;\"><br><br>So if action cannot be required, where does that leave us? It means that only <u>inaction</u> may reasonably be required (ideally on individual bases), <u>and</u> that:<br><br><center><span style=\"font-size: 32px;font-weight:900;\">Everyone chooses their own level of involvement</span></center><br><br>\"But wait! What about taxation?\" you ask... Good question. This <u>truth</u> means that taxation becomes optional and upon their <u>agreement to participate</u>, entitles one to the benefits of a system which must then <u>earn their business</u>.<br><br>Forced taxation always, eventually, results in a system that, in a vacuum of incentive or necessity to perform, fails its purpose of serving the public, just as does any public entity.<br><br></span><center style=\"font-family: courier;\">-end-</center></div>', 145, 31, 'whitehot robot', 'On Expectations', 'action can never be \"required,\" justifiably, but sometimes inaction may be.', 1, 1, '#philosophy #policy #taxation');
