(600033, '<div style=\"position: absolute;margin: 20px;background-color: #408;border-radius: 10px;cursor: pointer; padding: 5px;\"><a style=\"color: #0f4;\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cantelope.org/on_justification_and_reason.txt\">click here for an unformatted version</a></div><div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(&quot;https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/257Guj.jpg&quot;); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; line-height: 1.4em; text-shadow: rgb(0, 0, 0) 2px 2px 2px; text-align: justify;\" #ff8\"=\"\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 136, 34); font-size: 40px;\"><center><br></center><center><br></center><center><br></center><center><br></center><center>On Justification and Reason</center><br><br></span><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 20px; white-space: pre;\"><br></span><font color=\"#ff6\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">\"The end justifies the means,\" a famous saying calling into question the ethical/moral latitude of actions underneath a supposedly just umbrella, states that if the result is benevolent, the entire process is justified. This brutal formula is lacking a key consideration, the absence of which renders it incomplete and unable to support any claim of true morality.</span></font><br><br><font color=\"#ff6\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">The completeness of logic can make or break any formula, and when morality is its basis, the effects can be disastrous for many. <u>Constraints</u>, those things, actions, or behaviors that cannot enter into a formula (defined specifically or in terms of generalities),&nbsp;<u>must </u>cover and prohibit any subpart of a process from transgressing into moral territory which, irrespective of the \"ends,\" cannot independently be justified. So the <u>complete</u> true formula becomes:</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 30px;\"><center>The end justifies, <b>within established constraints</b>, the means.</center></span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">...thereby burdening the designer with the responsibility to consider wayward, potentially harmful effects caused by their so-called benevolent solution, and for which they must be answerable.</span><br></font><br><br><br><br><center style=\"font-family: courier;\">-end-</center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center></div>', 145, 17, 'whitehot robot', 'On Justification and Reason', '', 0, 0, '#philosophy'),
(600034, '<div style=\"position: absolute;margin: 20px;background-color: #408;border-radius: 10px;cursor: pointer; padding: 5px;\"><a style=\"color: #0f4;\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cantelope.org/competitions_domain.txt\">click here for an unformatted version</a></div><div style=\"padding: 20px; background-image: url(&quot;https://jsbot.cantelope.org/uploads/HvCyf.jpg&quot;); background-position: center center; background-repeat: no-repeat; background-size: cover; line-height: 1.4em; text-shadow: rgb(0, 0, 0) 2px 2px 2px; text-align: justify;\" #ace\"=\"\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: #fa8; font-size: 40px;\"><center><br></center><center><br></center><center>Competition\'s Domain</center><br></span><span style=\"font-family: courier; color: rgb(255, 255, 136); font-size: 20px; white-space: pre;\"><br></span><font color=\"#ace\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Many subjects or games lend themselves naturally to competition, whereas many do not. The dividing line between these categories is surprisingly clear and easy to define.</span></font><br><br><font color=\"#ace\" face=\"courier\"><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">In mathematics, a \"domain\" is the range of possible values returned by a function. To borrow this concept, the domain of competition is only those subjects or games in which the competitors may be evaluated on a strictly linear basis. A few examples, chess, checkers, poker, etc. have one winner and one or more losers based on a rigidly defined set of rules that boil down to a linear equation. Checkers, for example, concludes when one player captures the last of their opponent\'s pieces, whereas in poker, a numerical comparison of each player\'s hand-values places each of them on a linear (1-dimensional) graph, the top player being the winner, etc. These linear-type games, sports, races, etc. all have 1-dimensional, linear structures to determine the winner. But, some subjects, like beauty, art, music, literature, etc. are multidimensional and any attempt at linear competition becomes either meaningless or must truncate a dimension to make a linear analysis possible. Take a beauty contest for example, the entrants may all be beautiful, but the judges must decide which is <u>most</u>&nbsp;beautiful, frankly, a matter of opinion at best, and hardly quantifiable. But beauty exists and we all know it when we see it, so why can\'t it be quantified?</span><br><br><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Beauty, art, etc. and all multidimensional subjects have non-linear domains - that is, while we all recognize the basic \"axis\" of beauty, there exists a second dimension - that of individual preference, which extends from our own unique genders, sexual orientations, ethnicities, and formative experiences most importantly. This secondary dimension is the framework which guides, in the example of beauty, the primary dimension by way of evolution. Separately, and a subject for a different text, is the granular nature of evolution, occurring not on the level of life as a whole, nor as species, but individually, every time a creature or plant reproduces.<br><br>So an art or music competition, like a beauty contest, must disclaim that any \"victors\" are such only insofar as the judges evaluated them with <u>favoritism</u>.<br><br>There can be no objective \"most beautiful person,\" or \"best song,\" or \"most attractive art piece\" because, simply, such an analysis is mathematically impossible due to the complex nature of these and many other things.</span></font><br><br><br><center style=\"font-family: courier;\">-end-</center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center><center style=\"font-family: courier;\"><br></center></div>', 145, 26, 'whitehot robot', 'Competition\'s Domain', '', 0, 0, '#ph');
